2026-06-12 | Check If String Can Become K-Periodic After One Block Replacement

	Question
Return true if this is possible, otherwise false.
	Key Insight
If the final string is k-periodic, then all k-length blocks must be identical.
Since we can modify only one block:
		All blocks must already be the same
		or
		Exactly one block is different.
So the problem reduces to counting distinct blocks.
	Approach
1.	Split the string into substrings of length k.
2.	Count frequency of each block.
3.	Let totalBlocks = n / k.
4.	If there is only one distinct block:
		return true
5.	If there are exactly two distinct blocks:
		and one of them occurs exactly once
		then we can replace that block.
		return true
6.	Otherwise return false.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n/k)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    bool kPeriodic(string s, int k) {
        unordered_map<string, int> freq;
        int blocks = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < s.size(); i += k) {
            string part = s.substr(i, k);
            freq[part]++;
            blocks++;
        }
        if(freq.size() == 1)
            return true;
        if(freq.size() != 2)
            return false;
        for(auto &it : freq) {
            if(it.second == 1)
                return true;
        }
        return false;
    }
};
	Key Insight
After the operation, every k-sized block must be identical. Since only one block can be changed, at most one block may differ from the others initially. Therefore:
		number of distinct blocks ≤ 2
and if there are two distinct blocks, one of them must appear exactly once.
